{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84ba13c2-a6e4-4fea-a063-370a5a25f92a","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout.\n- `command`/`args` tell VS Code how to launch your server.\n- Once saved, open the Copilot chat in agent mode — it will auto-discover the tools your server exposes.\n\nIf you've already published a built binary, you can point directly to it instead:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"dotnet\",\n\"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7130ae36-ab76-4b46-beb9-6c7fc22b509e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"2C22:2ED2CA:28F6CEB:2D56BD1:69FD366E"},"id":"baa211af-39c0-4353-8da8-da5e63b9ffdc","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:03:52.752Z","parentId":"1a9e0577-c879-466d-99ba-89322c28e0f1"}
